{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3978c152-6d9e-4424-97b3-d735d818929d","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** downloads and installs the latest workload versions matching your current SDK. After a SDK update, your existing workload versions can fall out of sync — this command brings them back in line.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** only *reinstalls* the currently-installed versions. It fixes corrupted installations but won't upgrade anything, so it won't help if the issue is a version mismatch after a SDK update.\n\n**TL;DR:** `dotnet workload update` fixes version mismatches; `dotnet workload repair` fixes corrupted installs. You want the former.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88401055-232d-4836-8e42-37f181a9ace8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the installed SDK. This is what you want after a SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations. It doesn't change versions, it just re-downloads and reinstalls the current versions.\n\n\n- Since the workloads are out of sync with the new SDK, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to run.","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"1437:2EDED2:70192C3:784CD27:6A03CBB7"},"id":"ef32d279-2f82-47d9-ae4d-2592b2fae021","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:54:26.272Z","parentId":"de4a84fa-07f0-44a6-a29a-b79ca5cef519"}
